t there (or other such sites like gitlab or bitbucket). This helps us help you debug your code. Plus using Git helps you track the changes to your code over time, and when used effectively can be invaluable for those instances where a change breaks something and you can‚Äôt seem to ‚Äúundo‚Äù it. As long as you committed your code in git before you made those changes, you can always revert to that last committed code.</p>
<p>As for the code you posted, I‚Äôm having a very hard time following it, your boolean variables seem to denote the opposite of what their names imply. Ie you set <code>LimitReached</code> to <code>true</code> when you just checked that you hadn‚Äôt reached the limit and you set <code>BumperReleased</code> to <code>true</code> when you just checked that you are actively pressing the bumper. This makes it very hard to keep the code flow straight during analysis.</p>
<p>Though provided I have worked it out correctly, I don‚Äôt see any obvious issues in the code snippet provided, other than that I‚Äôm fairly certain it could be greatly simplified (see below). Based on your issues (the DigitalInput objects becoming null) it sounds like a scope issue, but I can‚Äôt be certain of that without the entire code. I also wonder if perhaps your switches are wired incorrectly? If you wired them such as they may cause a short circuit when triggered, that may be able to cause some weird issue with the RIO (though this is a totally left-field guess).</p>
<p>For the wiring, generally you wire the input to the ‚ÄúCOM‚Äù terminal of the switch, then 5v and gnd to either of the NO and NC terminals depending on desired state. You can also take advantage of the RoboRIO‚Äôs built-in Pull-Up resistors which will pull the input high if no voltage srouce/sink is connected to the input, then you don‚Äôt need to worry about wiring the 5v, you just need to connect gnd to either NO or NC, again based on your desired operation when you want the RIO to read true vs false.</p>
<hr>
<p>Here is an example of how I believe you could simplify your code. First, I reduced the number of variables. If you only want the motor to run when the motor is being held, you shouldn‚Äôt care about tracking when it was released, and you can check the state of the limit switches at any time. So what you really want to track is ‚Äúwhen can I move right vs left‚Äù. So I created two boolean variables for just that, leftLock and rightLock. These two should always be the opposite of each other since, according to your explanation, you wanted to only allow one direction of movement at a time until the limit is reached. Though we start with both false, since you state at the beginning you want to be able to go in either direction to start.</p>
<p>So with the variables reduced, we know that the primary trigger for them are the limit switches. So if we each each switch, we can adjust the locks appropriately, without involving our controller buttons or our outputs. Just checking our limit switches and adjusting our variables.</p>
<p>Then, with our current ‚Äúlimit state‚Äù known between our two variables, we can check if we are pressing the corresponding controller input to move in that direction, while also checking if we are allowed to move in that direction based on the lock variables. I also added code here to set the opposing lock variable if we decide on a direction so we can‚Äôt arbitrarily switch back and forth at the beginning, once a direction is picked, you are stuck with it until you reach the limit for that direction. But that could easily be removed without issue if desired.</p>
<p>Then finally, if neither moving condition is met (either because we aren‚Äôt pressing the button, or the direction we are pressing for is currently locked) we stop the motor.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">//Declaration
DigitalInput leftLimit, rightLimit;
boolean leftLock, rightLock;

//Initialization (robotInit)
leftLimit = new DigitalInput(5);
rightLimit = new DigitalInput(6);
leftLock = false;
rightLock = false;

//In Teleop 
if(leftLimit.get()) {
    leftLock = true;
    rightLock = false;
}
if(rightLimit.get()) {
    leftLock = false;
    rightLock = true;
}

if(leftBumper.get() &amp;&amp; !leftLock) {
    modTalon1.set(1.0);
    rightLock = true;
} else if(rightBumper.get() &amp;&amp; !rightLock) {
    modTalon1.set(-1.0);
    leftLock = true;
} else {
    modTalon1.set(0.0);
}
</code></pre>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2021-10-05T05:07:42.916Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":62,"readers_count":61,"score":62.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":396379,"topic_slug":"why-am-i-getting-weird-behavior-with-megatronix-mgt-magnetic-reed-switch","display_username":"Mykah","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":16897,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"She/Her üè≥Ô∏è‚Äç‚ößÔ∏è | 9153 | Programming and Electrical Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/why-am-i-getting-weird-behavior-with-megatronix-mgt-magnetic-reed-switch/396379/2","custom_user_title":"She/Her üè≥Ô∏è‚Äç‚ößÔ∏è | 9153 | Programming and Electrical Mentor","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":3,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2970618,"name":"Anand Rajamani","username":"asid61","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/asid61/{size}/7179_2.png","created_at":"2021-10-05T05:45:59.160Z","cooked":"<p>One small thing: if you‚Äôre using most FRC-legal motor controllers, you can wire the reed switch as a limit switch to them. That will automatically stop the motor from going further once it hits the switch.</p>
<p>If you are using a RoboRIO and CAN, you can then get the state of the limit switches (reed switches, in this case) to perform any additional behaviors like reversing direction.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2021-10-05T05:45:59.160Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":52,"readers_count":51,"score":55.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":396379,"topic_slug":"why-am-i-getting-weird-behavior-with-megatronix-mgt-magnetic-reed-switch","display_username":"Anand Rajamani","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":21715,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/why-am-i-getting-weird-behavior-with-megatronix-mgt-magnetic-reed-switch/396379/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":2}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2970624,"name":"Allen Nuttle","username":"nuttle","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/nuttle/{size}/124105_2.png","created_at":"2021-10-05T10:23:52.826Z","cooked":"<p>For the electrical hookup, the ‚Äúcom‚Äù connection on the sensor should go to a ‚Äú‚èö‚Äù (GND) pin on the roboRIO digital input.  You can connect either ‚ÄúNC‚Äù or ‚ÄúNO‚Äù on the sensor (not both, leave the other disconnected) to the ‚ÄúS‚Äù pin on the digital input.  You should not connect anything to the ‚Äú5V‚Äù pin on the digital input.  See <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/hardware/sensors/digital-inputs-hardware.html#connecting-a-simple-switch-to-a-dio-port">here</a>.</p>
<p>Using the ‚ÄúNC‚Äù connection on the sensor is best practice, as it means that if a wire comes loose, it is the same as the sensor picking up the magnet and indicating that things should stop.  In this case, the digital input will read false when the magnet is activating the sensor (or, again, if a wire comes loose).  If not, it will read true.</p>
<p>Test mode is a good way to make sure the electrical connections are right, and that the digital input is reading as you expect.  You can also use prints in the code or, better, send the raw digital input reading through network tables (to a dashboard).</p>
<p>This is a case where less code is probably a sign you have things right.  The point about connecting the limit switch directly to the motor controller is a pretty major one, and the general advice on the code (above) is also good.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2021-10-05T10:23:52.826Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":47,"readers_count":46,"score":34.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":396379,"topic_slug":"why-am-i-getting-weird-behavior-with-megatronix-mgt-magnetic-reed-switch","display_username":"Allen Nuttle","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/hardware/sensors/digital-inputs-hardware.html#connecting-a-simple-switch-to-a-dio-port","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Digital Inputs - Hardware ‚Äî FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":3}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":14283,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/why-am-i-getting-weird-behavior-with-megatronix-mgt-magnetic-reed-switch/396379/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2970635,"name":"Rod","username":"Weldingrod1","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/weldingrod1/{size}/162109_2.png","created_at":"2021-10-